WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:07.970
RETO MEIER: Today we find
out how it feels to be

00:00:07.970 --> 00:00:09.260
the eye in the sky.

00:00:09.260 --> 00:00:10.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: We learn
to stop worrying and

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:11.770
love the Weather Bomb.

00:00:11.770 --> 00:00:13.660
RETO MEIER: And we find out why
this week, neither one of

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:15.170
us are wearing pants.

00:00:15.170 --> 00:00:18.080
All in the next half hour on--

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:20.670
BOTH: The App Clinic.

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:21.980
RETO MEIER: Today we're looking
at weather apps

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:25.560
Weather Bomb, Eye in the Sky,
and Should I Wear Pants?

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:26.960
IAN NI-LEWIS: And then we're
going to dig a little deeper

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:30.700
into how Weather Bomb renders
its awesome map.

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:31.920
RETO MEIER: So let's
have a look at

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:34.070
weather apps in general.

00:00:34.070 --> 00:00:35.740
What are the things it
really needs in order

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:38.760
to be a good app?

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:40.740
IAN NI-LEWIS: Well obviously,
it needs to tell me today's

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:41.530
weather, right?

00:00:41.530 --> 00:00:43.520
RETO MEIER: That seems like
a pretty good start.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:44.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: Because obviously,
I don't want to get

00:00:44.850 --> 00:00:47.220
out of bed or open the window.

00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:47.800
RETO MEIER: Precisely.

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:49.160
That would be too much
to ask, right?

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:49.230
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:50.680
RETO MEIER: You want to be able
to know this stuff before

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:51.790
you get out of bed.

00:00:51.790 --> 00:00:54.000
It would also be nice to know
tomorrow's weather.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: And the seven
day forecast, I

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:56.730
would go for that.

00:00:56.730 --> 00:00:57.035
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:00:57.035 --> 00:00:59.760
All the things which mean that
you no longer are a slave to

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:01.250
the 11 o'clock news.

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:01.880
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:03.040
RETO MEIER: You also want
to have results that are

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:03.900
localized, right?

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:05.970
Something which knows where
you are to give you the

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:08.420
weather forecast for the city
that you're in, rather than

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:08.885
the general state.

00:01:08.885 --> 00:01:10.880
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's true, but
I don't necessarily want it

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:14.790
too local, because really, what
I want to know is how

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:17.640
cold or windy is it going to
be at the beach this time.

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:18.340
RETO MEIER: That's true.

00:01:18.340 --> 00:01:19.440
Which means you really
want to be able to

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:20.635
have multiple locations.

00:01:20.635 --> 00:01:22.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Can you tell we're
in northern California?

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:24.143
Because I didn't say how hot
and sunny is it going

00:01:24.143 --> 00:01:25.120
to be at the beach.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:25.620
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:29.290
And that's the thing where we
are here in sunny sometimes

00:01:29.290 --> 00:01:32.750
northern California, it's an
area of extreme microclimates.

00:01:32.750 --> 00:01:35.700
So localization of the weather
is really important, and the

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.670
ability to know which direction
you need to drive

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:40.300
for it to get less foggy is
kind of a killer feature.

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:42.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: Exactly.

00:01:42.020 --> 00:01:42.500
RETO MEIER: We're going to take

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:43.780
things up a little further.

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:45.740
What we really like to see is a
lot of the stuff that you're

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:48.290
used to seeing at the
11 o'clock news.

00:01:48.290 --> 00:01:51.150
Things like rich maps with sort
of more meteorological

00:01:51.150 --> 00:01:54.403
information, like topography
charts, satellites, those

00:01:54.403 --> 00:01:55.660
sorts of things.

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:58.350
IAN NI-LEWIS: And also I want to
see maps when I'm choosing

00:01:58.350 --> 00:01:59.030
my location.

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:01.240
RETO MEIER: Yeah, absolutely.

00:02:01.240 --> 00:02:03.630
That way you don't have to know
what city the beach is

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:05.930
in, you just point at
the each, job done.

00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:06.190
IAN NI-LEWIS: Oh, yeah.

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:08.949
Anytime I can get away from
putting in text to my mobile

00:02:08.949 --> 00:02:11.770
phone, excellent.

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:14.760
But I don't just want that,
because I'm super lazy, I also

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:15.330
want widgets.

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:18.070
I want to be able to see the
weather immediately when I

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:18.825
unlock my phone.

00:02:18.825 --> 00:02:20.910
RETO MEIER: In fact, I want to
go a step further and say,

00:02:20.910 --> 00:02:23.170
maybe there's a case here for
some rich notifications,

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:27.520
something which has a little sun
or cloud or whatever else,

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:29.070
and there's a really good
example of where you might

00:02:29.070 --> 00:02:31.270
want to use a low priority
notification.

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:33.300
So it doesn't pop up, it doesn't
ping me, but when I

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.400
pull down the slide, I've got
that extra information hand.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:38.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: Although I didn't
mind knowing what the

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:42.060
temperature is at all times
in my notification bar.

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:44.170
I thought that was kind
of a cool feature.

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:47.860
But of course, none of this is
going to be any good if your

00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:50.650
battery runs down all the time,
and so we're going to go

00:02:50.650 --> 00:02:54.490
ahead and beat this dead
horse one more time--

00:02:54.490 --> 00:02:58.200
all of these things depend on
efficient background updates

00:02:58.200 --> 00:03:01.380
that are done in a way that
won't drain your battery.

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:03.270
RETO MEIER: This is actually
another really good tip here,

00:03:03.270 --> 00:03:05.620
is that if you do want to do
your updates, say that you

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:08.250
know that the new weather
forecast comes in once a day,

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:10.670
so you want to wake up the phone
at 2:00 AM every morning

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:14.250
to get that new fresh weather
forecast each day, make sure

00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:16.840
that you're not doing that
at an exact time.

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:18.540
Because what you'll find is that
if everyone else is doing

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:20.710
the right thing and saying, look
we're not going to start

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:22.720
anything unless someone turns
on the phone to do this

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:26.240
update, you know you have to do
it then, suddenly you turn

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.390
on not just one user's device,
but everyone who has your app

00:03:29.390 --> 00:03:33.210
installed at the same time, and
then floods the bandwidth

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:34.930
with everyone else's
updates as well.

00:03:34.930 --> 00:03:36.850
So you want to make sure you're
making that this fuzzy

00:03:36.850 --> 00:03:37.840
is possible.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:41.760
2:00 AM-ish, plus or minus an
hour, so that you give your

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:44.880
servers a chance to not get
flooded, as well as the mobile

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:46.010
phone operator's bandwidth.

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:47.235
IAN NI-LEWIS: If only there
were an API that

00:03:47.235 --> 00:03:48.580
would do that for me.

00:03:48.580 --> 00:03:49.100
RETO MEIER: Indeed.

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:51.750
Something like an inexact
repeating alarm, perhaps.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:52.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: Really?

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:54.530
I'll have to keep
that in mind.

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:57.120
So let's go ahead and take
a look at our apps.

00:03:57.120 --> 00:03:57.970
RETO MEIER: Indeed.

00:03:57.970 --> 00:03:59.220
So you can see the icons
at the bottom.

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:02.400
We are going to start
with Weather Bomb.

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:03.650
IAN NI-LEWIS: Bomb-diddy-bomb-
di-bomb-bomb-diddy--

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:07.480
OK, sorry.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:09.320
RETO MEIER: So you can see here,
the feature page here,

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:11.530
it is a riot of color.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:14.740
Which is aptly depicted in their
app icon, which is in

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:18.089
fact a four color logo of
raindrops, I suppose.

00:04:18.089 --> 00:04:21.519
Slightly concerning, the concept
of there being four

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:23.190
colored raindrops.

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:26.650
But nonetheless, it is
consistent with their overall

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:30.510
UI or branding, I suppose, which
I guess is multi-color.

00:04:30.510 --> 00:04:32.670
I guess that's kind of their
killer feature, is the fact

00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:35.040
that they've got these multiple
overlays over the top

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:38.540
of their map views, which show
all these rich colors.

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:39.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah,
absolutely.

00:04:39.770 --> 00:04:42.850
RETO MEIER: That said, the
actual feature graphic itself,

00:04:42.850 --> 00:04:45.050
again, is falling into that trap
of looking a little bit

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:45.540
amateurish.

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:46.990
This is not an amateur app.

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:50.810
This has been really well put
together, but look here and it

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:52.540
just feels a little bit
like the bits are

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:53.650
pulled together, and--

00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:56.330
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, it hasn't
gotten within a few miles of a

00:04:56.330 --> 00:04:58.490
professional graphic
artist, I think.

00:04:58.490 --> 00:05:00.090
At least not the layout--

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:01.590
each little bit looks
really nice.

00:05:01.590 --> 00:05:02.010
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:03.710
So it's the composition here
that I think could

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:04.960
use a lot of work.

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.860
You want to avoid things like
italicized serifed fonts

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:10.140
within the feature graphic.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.340
Because again, as things get
smaller and smaller, they're

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:13.330
going to be harder to read.

00:05:13.330 --> 00:05:16.630
In fact, even from just a few
feet away, I'm getting the

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:19.100
impression that I may need to
either clean my glasses, or

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:21.410
update my prescription, because
I can barely read

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:22.810
insightful weather there.

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:24.340
IAN NI-LEWIS: This is something
that a lot of people

00:05:24.340 --> 00:05:27.200
get wrong, and don't even
realize until you see it on a

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:29.440
small device.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:33.540
If your logo, the app name and
your logo is not at least

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:37.930
twice as big as Weather Bomb
has, you're not going to be

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:41.270
visible on a lot of devices, and
you're not going to sell.

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:42.110
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:43.760
And you want to avoid
duplicating things.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.545
There's always a question of
whether you put the apps title

00:05:46.545 --> 00:05:48.270
and catch line in the
feature graphic.

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:50.940
There is certainly an argument
for that, but in this case,

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:52.980
it's not really adding anything
to the aesthetic.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:57.270
Similarly, you want to put the
app icon into feature graphic.

00:05:57.270 --> 00:05:59.530
You've already got the
multicolored raindrops, which

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:02.070
is that branding effect, but
you want to avoid actually

00:06:02.070 --> 00:06:03.160
duplicating content.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.790
Because as you can see here,
you're just sort of seeing the

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:08.200
same thing repeated over and
over again It just feels like

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:09.740
things were cut and pasted.

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:11.630
IAN NI-LEWIS: Also, I wouldn't
mind a slightly different

00:06:11.630 --> 00:06:14.210
treatment on the icon itself.

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:14.990
RETO MEIER: The rounded
corners.

00:06:14.990 --> 00:06:16.690
IAN NI-LEWIS: It looks
a little familiar.

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:21.260
Not just the rounded corners
but that little swatch of

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:23.300
color, like a reflection
across the top.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:24.580
RETO MEIER: That's
a good point.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:25.540
IAN NI-LEWIS: I've seen
that before and

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:27.040
it wasn't on Android.

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:28.290
RETO MEIER: It's an interesting
opportunity here,

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:30.870
because again, what we're
looking for is a unique

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:32.370
silhouette, something
which really stands

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:33.770
out and looks great.

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:37.780
So some sort of treatment here
that just removes the box as a

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:41.240
first step, and just has the
four raindrops would be an

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:42.670
interesting place to start.

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:43.360
IAN NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:44.970
RETO MEIER: So let's move on.

00:06:44.970 --> 00:06:46.540
Let's have a look at
the app itself.

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:49.470
So we're going to bring
up the giant phone.

00:06:49.470 --> 00:06:50.020
IAN NI-LEWIS: Giant phone?

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:50.600
Giant phone?

00:06:50.600 --> 00:06:51.740
There we go.

00:06:51.740 --> 00:06:56.400
All right, let's pull
the app up.

00:06:56.400 --> 00:06:59.530
There's a EULA at the
beginning, which is

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:00.990
unsurprising.

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:07.960
And then there is a page of text
which took me quite some

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:10.480
time to get past it
and understand.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:15.320
Not just to read it, but to
actually figure out how to

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:15.910
dismiss it.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:17.120
RETO MEIER: It's like you're
looking here, and it's like,

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:19.670
OK, so this is the wizard,
where's the OK button?

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:20.300
How do I--

00:07:20.300 --> 00:07:20.930
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:07:20.930 --> 00:07:23.820
IAN NI-LEWIS: We're going to do
a huge favor for all of our

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:29.270
viewers and show you how to get
to the second page of this

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:30.210
Weather Bomb app.

00:07:30.210 --> 00:07:33.950
And that is hit the refresh
button which shouldn't be

00:07:33.950 --> 00:07:36.030
there anyway,

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:36.640
RETO MEIER: It's an interesting

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:37.410
implementation here.

00:07:37.410 --> 00:07:39.900
They actually had a countdown
built into the refresh button,

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.060
which is interesting.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:45.160
But really, we're trying to get
to a point now, with app

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:47.770
design, where we can sort of
banish the refresh button.

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:49.570
A lot of users are still going
to want it there, particularly

00:07:49.570 --> 00:07:51.850
for things like weather or
email, where they're like,

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:54.470
seriously, I want to have
up to the second.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:56.530
But that's a good thing to put
in something like an overflow

00:07:56.530 --> 00:07:59.250
menu, so that it is there for
people who want it, but

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.050
ideally, no one does.

00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:03.320
Everything just refreshes and
does everything for you.

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:06.160
In an app like this, there is
that EULA at the beginning,

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:08.910
which is going to take some time
to someone at least look

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:10.890
at and dismiss if not
read through.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:12.710
That's a great time to
do that pre-cacheing.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:15.220
It only took a few seconds
to bring that first page

00:08:15.220 --> 00:08:16.570
information.

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:18.980
When someone downloads and opens
your app for the first

00:08:18.980 --> 00:08:23.750
time, they hit the icon, bypass
the EULA, and this is

00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:27.050
the first thing that they see,
this is pretty compelling.

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:27.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: It really is.

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:30.130
RETO MEIER: Compared to a page
full of text with a big bright

00:08:30.130 --> 00:08:32.070
red on black text right
at the start.

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:35.370
It's something you want to get
to awesomeness of your app as

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:36.409
quickly as possible.

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:37.580
And this looks awesome.

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:40.390
The previous page looked, again,
a little amateurish.

00:08:40.390 --> 00:08:42.210
IAN NI-LEWIS: I don't know if
the author of this app is

00:08:42.210 --> 00:08:44.420
running analytics, but it would
be fascinating to see

00:08:44.420 --> 00:08:45.860
just how much abandonment
there is--

00:08:45.860 --> 00:08:47.160
RETO MEIER: Yeah, what
is the drop of?

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:49.220
IAN NI-LEWIS: I know I probably
wouldn't have gone

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:52.500
through with it if it wasn't
my job to do so.

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:54.450
Which is not a ringing
endorsement.

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:58.630
The app itself did reward my
patience richly though.

00:08:58.630 --> 00:09:00.220
RETO MEIER: Yeah, and this
looks really nice.

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:01.760
We were talking about
the nice to have.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:05.020
I mean they've got a map here
at the start, and it seems

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:07.740
that if I drag left to right,
it's going to go through the

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:11.430
time and show this real time
map of satellite--

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:12.880
I guess it's rainfall
coverage.

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:13.540
That would make more sense.

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:16.570
IAN NI-LEWIS: I think you can
actually pick some different--

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:16.970
RETO MEIER: Oh, nice.

00:09:16.970 --> 00:09:20.240
IAN NI-LEWIS: There was
rain, we've got wind--

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:22.870
which is always nice to
know in this area.

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:24.810
RETO MEIER: A little
surprising.

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:26.350
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:09:26.350 --> 00:09:28.250
Now, the only thing that bugged
me about this map,

00:09:28.250 --> 00:09:31.380
actually, was that I had to
pinch to zoom on a reasonably

