On a slower device, or one
that doesn't have as much

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:57.100
memory bandwidth, or one that
just has different performance

00:30:57.100 --> 00:30:59.740
characteristics, you're going
to run a lot slower.

00:30:59.740 --> 00:31:02.900
17 milliseconds is really
on the edge.

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:06.190
It's actually just a little less
than 60 FPS, but that's

00:31:06.190 --> 00:31:10.720
the highest frame
time that I saw.

00:31:10.720 --> 00:31:13.630
So, what is eating
up all the time?

00:31:13.630 --> 00:31:14.970
Well it's not actually
the GPU.

00:31:14.970 --> 00:31:16.900
Now, you don't see it in this
view, because you have to run

00:31:16.900 --> 00:31:20.330
Systrace to see it, but the GPU
overhead on this is just

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:22.810
three to four milliseconds,
which isn't bad for something

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:25.200
that's drawing this
many pixels.

00:31:25.200 --> 00:31:29.110
No, what's really eating
up all the time

00:31:29.110 --> 00:31:32.090
is this over here.

00:31:34.660 --> 00:31:37.176
One draw call, 17
milliseconds.

00:31:41.130 --> 00:31:44.210
That's just one call, and it's
not even the one that touches

00:31:44.210 --> 00:31:45.100
the most pixels.

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:48.110
This is the call to
draw the overlay.

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:53.900
So what is it doing wrong?

00:31:53.900 --> 00:32:03.130
Well, the real problem is that
it's not just drawing these

00:32:03.130 --> 00:32:07.520
vertices, it's also memcopying
them, and that's really where

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:09.020
things get heavy.

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:12.700
There's actually two arrays here
that are being set up.

00:32:12.700 --> 00:32:15.300
And then they are being
drawn using this DL

00:32:15.300 --> 00:32:16.600
draw elements call.

00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:20.740
One of them is apparently, if
you look at the contents,

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:23.110
probably the weather
information itself.

00:32:23.110 --> 00:32:26.610
A bunch of integers, they kind
of cluster in odd ways.

00:32:26.610 --> 00:32:28.820
That's probably our weather
information.

00:32:28.820 --> 00:32:30.240
That's going to vary
per frame.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:33.810
Maybe not enough to
justify redoing it

00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:36.420
every frame, but yeah.

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:40.010
But the next one, which is even
larger, is a bunch of

00:32:40.010 --> 00:32:44.540
floats that are probably never
going to vary, because these

00:32:44.540 --> 00:32:48.650
are all the vertices that
go into this mesh.

00:32:48.650 --> 00:32:53.320
And there's no real reason
to change those ever.

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:56.510
Even if you're zooming the map
in and out, you can just

00:32:56.510 --> 00:32:58.000
change the projection
on those.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:33:02.070
So why are we sending
them every frame?

00:33:02.070 --> 00:33:02.690
There's no reason.

00:33:02.690 --> 00:33:05.480
Those should go in a vertex
buffer object.

00:33:05.480 --> 00:33:11.320
So, I think we'll go ahead
and sum up now.

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:14.700
There's nothing wrong with this
app, but it's skirting

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:19.750
the edge of going from buttery
to janky, and with just a few

00:33:19.750 --> 00:33:23.800
very, very slight changes,
it could be far

00:33:23.800 --> 00:33:26.060
